My client is a large automotive parts manufacturer headquartered in Toronto, Ontario.

According to the contact point at my client, on May 8, 2026, an individual named Brian, who was employed as the CFO of the company since 2017, came into the office of the President of the corporation and voiced his displeasure with the way in which he was being treated by the company. Specifically, according to Brian, the company made multiple promises to him that were not fulfilled, including a raise that was not given and a promise to hire an additional assistant for Brian that was not fulfilled. The President stated that he does not know what Brian is talking about, which resulted in Brian becoming more angry. In short, the two argued for quite some time, and Brian ultimately stated that he was quitting, barged out of the office, dropped off his laptop, keycard, and other company property with the receptionist prior to leaving the building, and did not honour any of his work obligations during the afternoon of May 8.

My client states that all of Brian’s claims related to unfulfilled promises are unfounded and that their internal corporate records show no proof of a promised raise that was not given or a promise to hire an employee that was not fulfilled.

At approximately 4:00pm on May 8, the President of the company instructed the HR department to prepare a job posting for a new CFO. A member of the HR department prepared the job posting over the weekend and informed the president on the evening of May 10 that it is ready to be posted when the President would like it to become publicly known that the job is available.

The job posting included the following details:
- The company’s name;
- The expected commitment (full time);
- The duties, which are standard duties for a CFO at a large employer;
- Preferred experience, which is described as 10+ years of financial experience, with at least 3+ years of experience as a senior executive at another company operating in the automotive space;
- Preferred education and qualifications, which included a preference for those with an accounting degree and CPA designation;
- Noted that compensation will be commensurate with experience and competitive with industry standards, and;
- Noted that the role will be a hybrid position with an expectation that the CFO be in-office three days per week.

The President informed a member of the HR department at 9:15am on May 11, 2026 that the job posting could be posted on all of the publicly available sites that the company usually posts job openings. Along with this, the President apologized to the member of HR for creating the work associated with hiring for another position, especially a senior executive, while the department was understaffed, but he did note that he believed that the HR department would be able to handle the task because using the company’s new AI candidate sorting system should allow the hiring process to move along more efficiently because it will highlight candidates whose qualifications meet the minimum threshold to be interviewed.

However, at approximately 8:30am that morning, Brian came into the office after not having spoken to anyone associated with my client since walking out on May 8. Brian briefly spoke with some colleagues in the accounting department and informed his assistant that he was excited to get back to work. Prior to beginning any work for the week, Brian spoke to the President’s assistant and requested to speak with the President so they could clear the air. The President’s assistant asked Brian to return at 9:30am, as he would be able to speak with Brian at that time.

As instructed, Brian returned to the President’s office at 9:30am. The President was visibly surprised to see that Brian had returned. Brian immediately began by apologizing for his actions on May 8, said that he is ready to return to work, and that he wanted to make it formally known that he is rescinding his resignation if his resignation was viewed as legitimate. The President told Brian that he accepts his apology and that he would normally be happy to have Brian return to work; however, that would not be possible in this instance because he already instructed the HR department to post the CFO opening and begin the search for a new employee. Brian attempted to explain that his resignation was made in the heat of the moment and that he did not miss any work days; however, the President did note that there was no contact made between Brian and the company for multiple days and that, as a result, the company believed that Brian intended to quit.

At that point, the conversation between Brian and the President concluded. Brian then drove home and began searching for available jobs online. One of the first openings that Brian saw was for his previous position, which was officially posted at 9:57am on May 11, 2026. Brian found this to be extremely strange, as he met with the President at 9:30am and their short conversation concluded prior to 9:40am.

Based on an application of the laws of Ontario as of May 11, 2026, evaluate whether there are any issues with the way in which my client handled Brian’s resignation and the associated posting of the CFO job opening at the company.
